This paper deals with motion control of robotic manipulators, which is a core topic in robotics. The use of the Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse and the issue of kinematic singularities are both common problems in robotics, which suggests that the paper is likely to be in the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper also proposes a new manipulability-based approach to motion control, which involves deriving a manipulability Jacobian and using it in a constrained quadratic program. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper's use of non-linear relationships and optimization techniques suggests that it may also be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's use of manipulability measures and end-effector velocities suggests that it may also be relevant to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
